[{"id":26967,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["4 - Hydroxypentan - 2-one","3- Hydroxypentan-2-one","1-Pentanol","2-Hydroxycyclopentanone"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3-Hydroxypentan-2-one and 4-Hydroxypentan-2-one will most readily be dehydrated to give alkene under acidic condition. This will lead to formation of&nbsp;&alpha;&minus;&beta;&nbsp;unsaturated ketone (conjugated system). But out of both 4-Hydroxypentan-2-one will most readily&nbsp;dehydrate to give alkene under acidic condition since the carbocation formed will be more stable than in the case of 3-Hydroxypentan-2-one.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Dehydration of 2-Hydroxycyclopentanone will lead to&nbsp;C=C&nbsp;double bond in 5 member ring that will cause strain and product is less likely to be formed.</p><p><img height=\"108\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/189e91b3-e084-4006-b414-668c02f934f9-image.png\" width=\"173\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (16 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26869,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3bb12f82-7c92-42fe-8e34-a79e852a6435.png\" style=\"width: 230px; height: 189px;\" />","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a9177679-a55e-4280-ba32-9388f7d12b45.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 203px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5917c281-18e4-465c-8d71-266b4928ee4b.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 180px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e710fd58-3e4b-452e-a059-c0efe2f7c49e.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 198px;\" /></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>In the first step protonation of alcohol takes place which leads to the formation of carbocation. Ring expansion takes place in the next step. In the given process five membered ring&nbsp;become six membered ring. Now, the carbocation loses proton in the presence of potassium hydroxide to give alkene.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d1843ca9-36f0-4d42-80a1-91fe5bc5640c.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 490px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26832,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/N1kkw6siR0z64giI2_Fo1wWM3CGidm8PUEY_rdoZqsE.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7VKh7wtpF6u3coEszSvBKlWIuQYn_c4mAFs98867HEs.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dzp7ghCvlohTnKXfEHh0BTZIp1WxKQahjtGGW6z0QG0.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/HNp6VzvbyJcAIUDhn_F8p8Iw5GB-Ae7eC_X-CK2r4hA.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4ZhDs7YCsOyg9GcNPqmxRjhuVD6CF8QavXrxKXNuyO8.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (8 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26932,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4534bdeb-ccf6-48b0-a877-ff30aceccedc-image.png\" style=\"width: 225px; height: 119px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ad25c486-eb1e-4a94-b501-4ed973176222-image.png\" style=\"width: 293px; height: 174px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5b7269c4-d286-4449-abf2-ed0263c66122-image.png\" style=\"width: 198px; height: 169px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7147e4ca-17e8-4956-bb05-78600a5979af-image.png\" style=\"width: 162px; height: 164px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/599b29fc-78fa-40aa-870b-e5f0c8bc082f-image.png\" style=\"width: 602px; height: 276px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b5fedf9d-3867-44f4-a0a9-4b28e09077b2-image.png\" style=\"width: 548px; height: 386px;\" /></p><p>Since the given question is single correct choice the best appropriate option is (A)</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (22 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26957,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d179ad44-9601-4cca-8b5a-40c5cbc99005-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 145px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3364fab8-1b60-4807-80f3-86dfa9b368c5-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 161px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bea95304-5446-426e-8d77-d48e28407f4c-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 187px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ff8ff7bb-c0c9-45af-abc1-53454cb0c61d-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 155px;\" /></p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1d306c99-4a3a-4603-824e-450497b6eb30-image.png\" style=\"width: 474px; height: 111px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26996,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Rate of reaction will be slow due to slow cleavage of carbon-halogen bond.","Alkene will be the main product.","Simple ether will form instead of mixed ether.","Expected mixed ether will be formed."],"answer":1,"solution":"The tertiary alkyl halide undergo elimination reaction to give alkenes\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/iwwruheRKnzmYkV1Z3uJnWbqBcypfmbHiXzs8-i2fTY.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Q5keBSCu7a1m5VBDi9fIqciQhiJE5qzP2DqdYC5bkjI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26862,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/79b5cd08-5431-4f83-9d92-f3f9ce94aea6.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 122px;\"/>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>NaOH</mi><mo> </mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CCl</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>NaOH</mi><mo> </mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>HCCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>NaOH</mi><mo> </mo></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Salicylaldehyde is prepared by heating phenol and chloroform together in the presence of potassium hydroxide or sodium hydroxide. This reaction is called the Reimer-Tiemann reaction.</p><p>The Reimer Tiemann reaction is an organic chemical reaction where phenol is converted into an ortho hydroxy benzaldehyde using chloroform, a base, and an acid workup. This reaction can also be described as the chemical reaction used for the ortho-formylation of phenols.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fbeaa419-2601-4d1e-90e3-57d35126c142.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 146px;\"/></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26829,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A-III, B-IV, C-II, D-I","A-IV, B-I, C-II, D-III","A-IV, B-III, C-II, D-I","A-III, B-IV, C-I, D-II"],"answer":1,"solution":"Unsaturation (Baeyer's test) involves decolorization of the reagent, represented by discharge of color (IV).<br>Alcoholic groups (Ceric ammonium nitrate test) produce a red color (I).<br>Aldehyde groups (Tollen's reagent) produce a characteristic silver mirror effect (II).<br>Phenolic groups (FeCl₃ test) produce a violet or pink color (III).<br>The correct matching is A-IV, B-I, C-II, D-III.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26945,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/559a6e0d-e4ae-48ff-8d0a-a60da83e2063-image.png\" style=\"width: 119px; height: 141px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/572f4a58-c484-403a-a7cd-85d16009b74a-image.png\" style=\"width: 116px; height: 139px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5bdd3d4c-7fc8-4dc8-8857-6e5b1a3efdd6-image.png\" style=\"width: 127px; height: 138px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8132b27b-d657-4550-9148-280ca9d32822-image.png\" style=\"width: 115px; height: 139px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e3d1703c-5b0e-4d7f-8c73-20e4cd3012d4-image.png\" style=\"width: 370px; height: 320px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;is attached to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>OH</mi></math>&nbsp;group to make it good leaving group and elimination takes place and alkene is formed as it is in conjugation with carbonyl group.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26860,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true","Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true but R is NOT the correct explanation of A."],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math> is a measure of  the acidity of a particular molecule. It measures the strength of an acid by how tightly a proton is held by a Bronsted acid. The lower the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math>, the stronger the acid and the greater its ability to donate its protons. describe the acidity of a particular molecule.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>logK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math></p><p>Hence, Assertion is true,</p><p>Phenol is more acidic than ethanol because after losing a proton <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mfenced></math>, phenol forms phenoxide ion which is stabilised by resonance whereas ethoxide ion is not.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26852,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4H6ls5uDi078n8XR6s_daSbfir3TUrwUsq0w5Lti_f8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/O6qf_tLMBf8sxt5v6_tleQzCh-4Ps4XoqMjpNk0MZk8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EeUymD8AmemYoUtd5MTApSnUpVKABPdb8ECIaa3vvdQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3ql8MmLk46Iaf-z0W0t26t5YdzH5GDe9L0yLWHvn97Q.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/kzAmFBeK7yHb2zLbNGEtCfJejUnCyBAp1rL0AarTO7s.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26876,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Reaction of Ketone with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>RMgBr</mi></math> followed by hydrolysis.","Reaction of alkyl halide with aqueous <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math>.","Hydroboration-oxidation of alkene.","Ozonolysis of alkene"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Reacting a Grignard reagent with a ketone gives a tertiary alcohol. When alkyl halide reacts with aqueous sodium hydroxide to give alcohol, the reaction is called nucleophilic substitution. The Hydroboration Oxidation reaction is an organic chemical reaction which is employed for the conversion of alkenes into alcohols that are neutral. Reductive ozonolysis of alkenes will lead to formation of aldehyde or ketones, oxidative ozonolysis of alkenes will lead to formation of carboxylic acids or ketones.</p><p>So, alcohol is not formed by ozonolysis of alkenes.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26824,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Fehling solution","Lucas reagent","2, 4 - DNP reagent","Saturated $\\mathrm{NaHSO}_{3}$ solution"],"answer":0,"solution":"Acidic hydrolysis of vinyl ethers involves the addition of water across the double bond followed by the elimination of alcohol/phenol to form carbonyl compounds. In the given reaction:<br>$CH_3-CH=CH-O-C(CH_3)=CH_2 \\xrightarrow{H_3O^+} P + Q$<br>The hydrolysis occurs at both vinyl ether linkages.<br>The left part $CH_3-CH=CH-O-$ hydrolyzes to form propanal: $CH_3-CH_2-CHO$ (P).<br>The right part $-O-C(CH_3)=CH_2$ hydrolyzes to form acetone: $CH_3-CO-CH_3$ (Q).<br>P is an aldehyde (propanal) and Q is a ketone (acetone).<br>Fehling solution is used to distinguish between aldehydes and ketones. Aldehydes (except benzaldehyde) reduce Fehling solution to give a red precipitate of $Cu_2O$, while ketones do not react.<br>Lucas reagent is used for alcohols. 2,4-DNP reacts with both aldehydes and ketones. Saturated $NaHSO_3$ reacts with most aldehydes and methyl ketones, so it is not the best choice for distinguishing these specific compounds compared to Fehling solution.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26984,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Alcohols are weaker acids than water","Acid strength of alcohols decreases in the following $\\mathrm{RCH}_2 \\mathrm{OH}>\\mathrm{R}_2 \\mathrm{CHOH}>\\mathrm{R}_3 \\mathrm{COH}$","Carbon-oxygen bond length in methanol, $\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{OH}$ is shorter than that of $\\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{O}$ bond length in phenol.","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5ExyATau-N6w3qp9kB9Nz1KWV5MsSwtJNZD2ZEbB0Nw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"The $\\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{O}$ bond length in alcohols is $142 \\mathrm{pm}$ and in Phenol it is $136 \\mathrm{pm}$. The $\\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{O}$ bond length in phenol is shorter than that in methanol due to the conjugation of unshared pair of electrons on oxygen with the ring, which imparts double bond character to the $\\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{O}$ bond.\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/T2GHl5yGG9U3MbJEjzjdYq4obgdPGiZth9mbVQzhoPc.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/T18uTADgbNHXE0FPE2a1ceLXICafPh1GxTDkzDAdZRQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26918,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-pentene","proponaldehyde","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-butene","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>-methylpent-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-ene"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6b668b71-3579-49c2-86dd-354c73feaa3c-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 144px;\" /></p><p>Hex-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>-ene-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-ol on reaction with PCC forms&nbsp;Hex-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>-ene-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-one.</p><p>Hex-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>-ene-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-one on iodoform reaction gives pent-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;enoic acid and iodoform.</p><p>Pent-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;enoic acid on decarboxylation with soda lime forms but-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-ene.&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26961,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["m-Cresol","o-Toluidine","Oleic acid","Benzamide"],"answer":0,"solution":"Meta-cresol <br/><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/83422d3f-fef6-4c07-a8df-15acc24d06da-image31.png\"> <br/>the group should be base sensitivity means it should have acidic hydrogen because it is soluble in <math><mn>10</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> and it should be less acidic than <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math> because it is insoluble in <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>.</mo></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26964,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"151\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/551a77c2-11f5-4c5f-af3d-7b1da2411748-image.png\" width=\"131\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"117\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f4127ada-6f7b-4590-b6a8-cd5ddbbbbf9d-image.png\" width=\"140\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"139\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/291ef586-b2ad-4f4a-9446-7532c72a1b33-image.png\" width=\"144\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"124\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6c109fda-67de-4517-8ce6-3b13f7b217f9-image.png\" width=\"123\" /></p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Initially&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>hydroxy toluene reacts with sodium hydroxide to form acid-base reaction and by following this reaction nucleophile is form which later shows nucleophilic substitution reaction as shown below:</p><p><img height=\"117\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/28f37fb2-fc68-4355-946d-5ba2055cefde-image.png\" width=\"635\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26993,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/her1MklRhrJ6nqwRqExSXl1zvLCmozlycURr4isp6uE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/oHCSATOwJbrIODo3zseN1pSmhIln23iYcaMg15tYDig.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/mtlBdTlAp8sIpYA_M0Ik7Dx9QGKk2WHF2ZRAAoP-L3k.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_y62KhDqe7QKt_XFaQqKOdZ-Haxonnm9YsN0Re8oX0U.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/gy9AQ2DmSVP-rXdhbGq3lqzqbcSrtnqy8rmgABI5wSI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (23 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26901,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6c1ac2cd-0275-4054-803b-d32222543b92-image.png\" style=\"width: 289px; height: 120px;\" /></p><p>In the above reaction the Ethyl group of grignard reagent acts as a strong base.</p><p>As per the stoichiometric equation the number of moles of methanol is equal to the number of moles of ethane.</p><p>Volume of methanol<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math>Volume of ethane<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>24</mn><mi>ml</mi></math></p><p>Hence, number of moles of ethane</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>24</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>22</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Weight of the gas= Number of moles<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#215;</mo></math>&nbsp;Molecular mass</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>mg</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26938,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"187\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/10dc6609-85dc-49d3-ade1-736be2ee9e13-image.png\" style=\"float: left;\" width=\"102\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img height=\"171\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ee915427-d4f2-4385-8514-9190689fb3ee-image.png\" style=\"float: left;\" width=\"128\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"171\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c4d7774f-ef4f-4ddb-8c10-f9527d834319-image.png\" style=\"float: left;\" width=\"116\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"157\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2aae8672-e206-4b0f-95ad-5a681c1d3006-image.png\" style=\"float: left;\" width=\"82\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1d8e874f-9aec-4839-bfd4-e48c897e7b8f-image.png\" style=\"width: 342px; height: 205px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26972,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/yevreorhuwsdqykvbivbyfgfmrtdiljphpusswqlcwcgsrahya.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ivcmudltsyyvkxpfnzrgwnbwfbchtqcwgijtydkxgiluisvuel.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ceahixwyhzvyxpkwdilkeplwrvogeiqmtvykaajsfuofshzndp.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/skrqoidzvztbbfpukwhscbvgujaopadlkodeooomxejevrbmfd.jpeg\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Two different reactions are taking place here Kolbe&ndash;Schmitt reaction and esterification reaction (treatment of the product of Kolbe&ndash;Schmitt reaction with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ester</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>.</mo></math>&nbsp;</p><p>The two reactions can be written as follows:</p><p>1.Kolbe&ndash;Schmitt reaction: reaction of phenol with carbon dioxide in the presence of sodium hydroxide, followed by acidification converts phenol to&nbsp;1&minus;1&minus;&nbsp;hydroxybenzoic acid (Salicylic acid).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>2.Esterification reaction: The salicylic acid is then reacted with acetic anhydride&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo></math>to form aspirin.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img alt=\"solution\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1159994_1033119_ans_afd2281d9c97440b830fea6c7a7e2b91.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 142px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":26937,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>iii</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>ii</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>iii</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"(a) Alcoholic potassium hydroxide<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math>used for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo></math>elimination<br />(b) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pd</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>BaSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo></math> Lindlar&#39;s catalyst<br />(c) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>BHC</mi></math> (Benzene hexachloride)<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math>Obtained by addition reactions<br />(d) Polyacetylene<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math>Electrodes in batteries","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26960,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/188122d2-c607-4732-9498-ea663e54caf6-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 173px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d2011288-83f8-4263-82fb-6f4ce058a285-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 140px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b1b54412-77af-4cea-ba1b-c36d528744c1-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 111px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/14b103f3-63ad-40b3-a6b5-cfb277247928-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 129px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/21d09c92-0ee3-46a4-a804-95bdb3c97d26-malakdo.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 331px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26848,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c7BiJ3gSK2WAiUOvXdiFAPmSWRNgPaqzAgQju5Uedqw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","\\(\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{OH}\\)","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/O0j_-o5h2qGohYZF5XPKjx-pdGLNi_MK8hhiitxnNFo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/wg3rLJFNKFY8YNzpVDqjQDJXIWMPgGR5Mt6YsgXXFU4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/mTigbHiRCC-VmZx8FrziBspvRpWqGpgdcB-h-3urZXw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26837,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCH}_3, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{OH}, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}(\\mathrm{Br}) \\mathrm{CH}_3$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCH}_3, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}(\\mathrm{OH}) \\mathrm{CH}_3, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}(\\mathrm{Br}) \\mathrm{CH}_3$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CHO}, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{OH}, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{Br}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CHO}, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}=\\mathrm{CH}_2, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}(\\mathrm{Br}) \\mathrm{CH}_3$"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Kd2fTID3HFrs44KIApVbCkSyqiTXhtPTbyRdhtPOP6M.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26843,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false"],"answer":1,"solution":"Statement I is correct as boiling point of alcohol phenols increase with increase in the number of C -atoms due to increase in van der Waals forces.\nStatement II is correct, since alcohols phenols have intermolecular H -bonding therefore their boiling points are higher in comparison to other class of compounds such as ethers, haloalkanes.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26827,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["","","",""],"answer":0,"solution":"The mixed ether (P) upon heating with conc. HI undergoes cleavage to form two different alkyl iodides.<br>Treatment with aq. NaOH converts these iodides to alcohols (Q) and (R).<br>Both (Q) and (R) giving yellow precipitate with NaOI indicates both are secondary or primary alcohols capable of iodoform reaction.<br>For both cleavage products to yield iodoform-positive alcohols, the mixed ether must have both alkyl groups capable of forming such alcohols.<br>Option (1) represents a symmetric mixed ether where both fragments upon HI cleavage yield alcohol products with methyl groups adjacent to OH (secondary alcohols) or methyl ketones after oxidation, both giving positive iodoform test.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26882,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["a &gt; d &gt; b &gt; c","b &gt; d &gt; c &gt; a","b &gt; a &gt; d &gt; c","d &gt; b &gt; c &gt; a"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The dehydration of alcohol takes place via the formation of a&nbsp;carbocation. Hence, the rate of reaction depends on the stability of carbocation.</p><p>No dehydration is possible in phenol because carbocation formation is difficult in case of phenol.</p><p>Option (d) fast due to loss of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;conjugation increasing stable of compound as compared to (c). Option(b) is very fast because stable compound formed.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26922,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9c4b43c5-1f57-4e02-ae8d-82a6b09cdbbe-image.png\" style=\"width: 248px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6a708608-5bf4-4972-aceb-b877a615fc08-image.png\" style=\"width: 255px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f9a4e151-8003-4371-8ec4-6230a34c594f-image.png\" style=\"width: 230px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/af00c275-d1ed-402a-b40c-a377e624800f-image.png\" style=\"width: 268px; height: 200px;\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d893fa6b-a4d7-4972-9531-f47a6198b250-3229c4e5-c5d2-47ff-a71d-ff1031c4e979-image(1).png\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 141px;\" /></p><p>It is a bimolecular nucleophilic substitution reaction.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 2)","image":null}]